<div id="PJA12d192" class="doc letter">

<h2>From C. W. F. Dumas</h2>

<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight">Lahaie Lundi 25e. fevr. 1782</td>
		</tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Lhonore vtre dhier ma rendu heureux en mapprenant que vous approuvez ma conduite.</p>
<p>Je me suis transport tout de suite chez Madame la Comtesse de Wickrad, qui ma dit quil ne lui toit pas possible de terminer plutt ses affaires ici, et entrautres le transport formel de la maison, avant le 1er. May prochain; que si cependant, contre les apparences pr-<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0271">[271]</span>sentes, elle pouvoit gagner quelque temps, elle men feroit avertir. Il faudra donc laisser les choses comme elles sont,  mon grand regret: car jaimerois trs-fort vous avoir ici ds aujourdhui plutt que demain. Je lavois dj sonde l-dessus avant de conclure vendredi, et elle avoit rpondu par la Ngative. Cela nempechera pas que vous ne puissiez vuider votre maison  Amsterdam et embarquer touts vos effets, et les expdier pour ici le 1er. de May en un seul bateau; car ds le lendemain votre maison leur est ouverte, pour y tre placs, et puis le 3e May rangs selon vos desirs<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n1" id="PJA12d193n1-ptr">1</a> car  la rigueur, la Comtesse ne peut tre oblige  sortir de la maison avant le 3e. May, et de cette maniere il vous en cotera moins.</p>
<p>La rponse que la Comtesse a donne au Coureur<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n2" id="PJA12d193n2-ptr">2</a> quand il a demand qui toit lacheteur, a t que la maison avoit t achete pour le Congrs. Il ny a pas de mal  cela. Cela doit avoir occasionn une plaisante sensation.</p>
<p>Aprs avoir demand si ce que lon mavoit assur toit aussi certain que lon me lavoit dit, on ma rpondu que si la rsolution ntoit pas prise dj, lon toit assur quelle ne tarderoit pas.</p>
<p>Pour revenir  votre Htel, je suis extrmement chagrin de la circonstance o nous nous trouvons, mon Epouse et moi, de devoir dmnager aussi au 1er de May prochain. Par les mesures que nous avions prises pour cette anne ds la fin de la passe, jai lou des chambres ici pour moi ds le commencement de ce mois, et ma femme et ma fille se prparent  partir le 1er. de May, et peut-tre auparavant, pour notre Ferme en Gueldre, o elles passeront toute la bonne saison; et lhyver ici ou ailleurs, selon que nos circonstances le rendront convenable. Il mest donc bien facheux, Monsieur, de ne pouvoir vous offrir, outre mon assistance, sur laquelle vous pouvez compter, celle aussi de mon Epouse, trs-suprieure  la mienne pour ce qui regarde les rparations de la maison, le placement et larrangement de vos meubles, lemplete de celles que vous voudriez y ajouter, le nettoyage, &amp;c. &amp;c. avec les prcautions, le soin et loeconomie, que les Dames entendent gnralement mieux que nous autres hommes. Elle partage vivement avec moi la mortification que ce contre-temps nous cause; et nous voudrions de tout notre coeur y remdier, sil toit possible. Si javois prevu ce qui vient darriver, jaurois pu retenir la maison que joccupe encore, une anne de plus. Mais il nen est plus temps. Cette maison est loue  un autre locataire, et nous devrons en sortir comme jai dit.</p>
<p>Il y a un homme ici, qui ayant appris que vous avez achet lhtel, est venu moffrir une tenture de chambre, rideaux, &amp;c. assortis. Je <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0272">[272]</span>lirai voir, ds quune indisposition qui ma pris hier et aujourdhui, sera passe. Je prierai ensuite mon Epouse de voir aussi Si elle est aussi belle et aussi bon march que cet homme le dit, et Si elle conviendra pour la couleur et la mesure  celles de vos meilleurs appartemens qui pourra en avoir besoin, aprs quoi je pourrai vous en parler ou crire plus amplement.</p>
<p>On ma prsent aussi un beau fourneau de fer fondu, qui avoit servi un seul hiver dans le Vestibule des Domestiques dun Envoy mort ici. Il est tout neuf encore. Je sais quil a t achet pour 7 Ducats. Je puis lavoir pour 28  30 florins, parce que la personne qui me la dit lauroit pris pour elle-mme, sil ntoit pas un peu trop grand pour son appartement. Mais il faut se dterminer dabord sur cet article. Si vous le voulez, Monsieur, je lacheterai pour vous. Il ne ferme point en bas; et lon a lagrment dy voir brler le feu comme  la grille dune Chemine.</p>
<p>Aprs avoir lu  Mon Epouse ce qui la regarde dans cette Lettre, elle ma dit quelle mettra elle-mme par crit ses conseils pour votre dmnagement, et surtout pour le nettoyage de votre htel ici, avant larrangement de vos meubles. Je vous enverrai son Ecrit ds que je laurai.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n3" id="PJA12d193n3-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>Je ne Sai Si je vous ai parl, Monsieur, de la rflexion quon fait gnralement ici, quil ny avoit que la France et lEspe, queussent des htels ici en propre, et que lAmrique sest monte sur leur ton.</p>
<p>Certaines paroles chappes, et que jai entendues par hazard, me font juger que bientt nous serons dlivrs ici de certain espionage. Mes complimens  Mrs. Barclai et Thaxter. Je suis avec un grand respect, Monsieur, Votre trs-humble &amp; trs-obissant serviteur</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="PJA12d193" class="trans letter">

 <h2>C. W. F. Dumas to John Adams: A Translation</h2>
 
<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight">The Hauge, Monday 25 February 1782</td>
		</tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I was happy to be informed, by your honored letter of yesterday, of your approval of my conduct.</p>
<p>I went immediately to see the countess of Wickrad, who told me that she could not finish her business here, among other things the transfer of the house, sooner than May 1st. If she is able to gain some time, contrary to present expectations, she will alert me to it. To my regret, things must stay the same then, since I would very much like to have you here today rather than tomorrow. I had already inquired about it before finishing Friday, but she said no. This does not mean that you cannot empty your house in Amsterdam, and load all of your effects and send them on one<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0273">[273]</span> boat to arrive on May 1st. The next day your house will be open for them to be placed there, and then on the 3rd of May, to be arranged according to your wishes.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n1" id="PJA12d193n1-ptr">1</a> Then, if need be, the countess will not have to leave the house before May 3rd and therefore it will cost you less money.</p>
<p>When the courier<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n2" id="PJA12d193n2-ptr">2</a> asked the Countess about the buyer, her reply was that the house was bought for Congress. There is nothing bad about that. This must have caused a pleasant sensation.</p>
<p>After having asked if what had been assured me was as certain as what I had been told, the answer was that if the resolution were not already passed, it would be soon.</p>
<p>Back to the house business, I am extremely distressed at the situation that my wife and I find ourselves in, that is, that we must also move before next May 1st. Because of steps taken for this year at the end of last year, I rented rooms for me here beginning this month, and my wife and daughter are preparing to leave on May 1st, or perhaps sooner, for our farm in Gelder. They will pass the summer there and the winter here or elsewhere depending on our circumstances. It is regrettable, sir, that I cannot offer you my wifes assistance, in addition to my own, on which you can rely. Her assistance is superior to mine regarding home repairs, furniture arrangement, new purchases, cleaning, etc., because of the precautions, care, and economy that women generally understand better than men do. She deeply shares with me the mortification of this contretemps, and we would, with all our hearts, remedy it if we could. If I had anticipated what was going to happen, I would have been able to retain the house for another year. But there is no more time. This house is rented to another tenant and we must leave as I said.</p>
<p>There is a man here, who, after learning who bought the house, offered me an assortment of wall coverings and curtains. I will go to see them as soon as I recover from a small upset. I will then ask my wife to go see them also to check if they are as beautiful and well priced as this man says. If she thinks the color and size would be suitable for your best rooms, I will talk to you or write to you about them in more detail.</p>
<p>Also I was offered a nice cast iron stove that was used for only one winter in the servants vestibule of an envoy here who passed away. It is still completely new. I know it was bought for 7 ducats. I could have it for 28 or 30 florins because the person who told me about it wanted it for himself, but it was too big for his apartment. But first it must be decided upon. If you want it, sir, I will buy it for you. It does not close at the bottom and one has the pleasure of watching it like a fire in a hearth.</p>
<p>After reading to my wife what I wrote about her in this letter, she told me that she will write to you herself regarding your move, and especially regarding the cleaning of your house here before your furniture arrives. I will send her letter as soon as I have it.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d193n3" id="PJA12d193n3-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>I do not know if I told you, sir, of the remark generally being made here. It is being said that it has been France and Spain who have had residences here exclusively, and now America has equaled them in stature.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0274">[274]</span>
<p>By chance, I heard talk that we will soon be spared from certain espionage here. My compliments to Mr. Barclay and Mr. Thaxter. I am with great respect, sir, your very humble and very obedient Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Dumas</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="PJA12d193sn1">
<p>
